  "text": "In the next protocol ( Fig. 7 ) , to determine whether or not constitutively active channels regulate bulk average [Ca 2+ ] c , the electrochemical driving force for Ca 2+ entry via voltage-dependent Ca 2+ channels was increased by hyperpolarization to Ϫ 130 mV (from Ϫ 70 mV). A 60-mV hyperpolarization increases the electrochemical driving force acting on Ca 2+ by an amount equivalent to a 100-fold increase in extracellular [Ca 2+ ] (i.e., to 300 mM). Hyperpolarization ( Ϫ 130 mV) increased bulk average (0.66 ± 0.26 ⌬ F/F 0 ) and subplasma membrane [Ca 2+ ] (1.1 ± 0.44 ⌬ F/F 0 ) ( Fig. 7 ) . The same hyperpolarization applied again some 60 s later evoked a comparable rise in [Ca 2+ ] in the bulk cytoplasm (0.75 ± 0.31 ⌬ F/F 0 ) and subplasma membrane space (1.03 ± 0.35 ⌬ F/F 0 ) ( Fig. 7 ) . Next, in the same cell, the hyperpolarization protocol was repeated but, in this case, 1 μ M nimodipine was applied to block voltage-dependent Ca 2+ channels before the second hyperpolarization occurred ( Fig. 7 ) . In these experiments, hyperpolarization (to Ϫ 130 mV from Ϫ 70 mV) evoked an increase in [Ca 2+ ] c (0.77 ± 0.24 ⌬ F/F 0 ) and [Ca 2+ ] PM (0.82 ± 0.24 ⌬ F/F 0 ; n = 5). 1 μ M nimodipine blocked neither the hyperpolarizationevoked increase in the bulk cytoplasm (0.99 ± 0.35 ⌬ F/ F 0 ; n = 5; P > 0.05) nor subplasma membrane space (1.1 ± 0.34 ⌬ F/F 0 ; n = 5; P > 0.05) ( Fig. 7 ) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . If the dihydropyridine-sensitive channel determines resting values, the blocker will reduce [Ca 2+ ] c . As a part of the protocol, the inhibitory effi cacy of nimodipine on voltage-dependent Ca 2+ channels was confi rmed. In a second separate protocol, the effects of nimodipine on the Ca 2+ infl ux that follows a prolonged (2.5-s) hyperpolarization to Ϫ 130 mV was examined. Hyperpolarization increases the electrochemical driving force on Ca 2+ to increase entry of the ion. If voltage-dependent Ca 2+ channels are constitutively active they will remain so regardless of the membrane potential (because of PKC ␣ phosphorylation), and nimodipine should reduce Ca 2+ entry and [Ca 2+ ] rise. 1 μ M nimodipine, applied by pressure ejection from a nearby puffer pipette, rapidly blocked the Ca 2+ current and rise in [Ca 2+ ] c , but did not reduce [Ca 2+ ] c at the resting membrane potential ( Ϫ 70 mV) ( Fig. 6 ) . Thus, depolarization ( Ϫ 70 to +10 mV) activated a voltagedependent Ca 2+ current (I Ca ) and increased [Ca 2+ ] c ; the latter returned toward basal levels when the depolarization had ended ( Fig. 6 ) . Next, the blocker nimodipine (1 μ M) was applied from the puffer pipette. Little change in [Ca 2+ ] c occurred. Resting bulk average [Ca 2+ ] c was 1.03 ± 0.026 before (F/F 0 ) 1 μ M nimodipine and 0.99 ± 0.035 after (F/F 0 ; n = 8; P > 0.05) ( Fig. 6 ) . Neither did resting [Ca 2+ ] PM change before (1.1 ± 0.044 F/F 0 ) and after (1.04 ± 0.051 F/F 0 ; n = 8; P > 0.05) 1 μ M nimodipine. Although nimodipine was ineffective in altering resting [Ca 2+ ] c , I Ca and its accompanying [Ca 2+ ] c increase were blocked ( Fig. 6 ) . Thus, in control, depolarization-evoked ( Ϫ 70 to +10 mV) I Ca averaged Ϫ 89 ± 21 pA and [Ca 2+ ] rise in the bulk cytoplasm 4.1 ± 1.2 ( ⌬ F/F 0 ) and subplasma membrane space 4.7 ± 1.4 ( ⌬ F/ F 0 ; n = 8). After 1 μ M nimodipine, I Ca ( Ϫ 13 ± 3 pA; P < 0.01) and the accompanying [Ca 2+ ] rise in the bulk cytoplasm (0.37 ± 0.13 ⌬ F/F 0 ; P < 0.05) and subplasma membrane space (0.49 ± 0.17 ⌬ F/F 0 ; n = 8; P < 0.05) were each signifi cantly reduced. After a further ‫ف‬ 3 min, I Ca ( Ϫ 59 ± 23 pA) and the [Ca 2+ ] c rise in the bulk cytoplasm 2.3 ± 0.75 ( ⌬ F/F 0 ) and subplasma membrane because of SR store depletion. In contrast, the depolarization-evoked [Ca 2+ ] increase was not reduced in either subplasma membrane space or bulk cytoplasm. After inhibition of the caffeine-evoked [Ca 2+ ] increase, the depolarization-evoked [Ca 2+ ] PM or [Ca 2+ ] c increase were not reduced. Furthermore, localized increases in regions of the subplasma membrane space measured by TIRF (red line in inset in C) were more rapid in onset and decline than those seen in average measured in the subplasma membrane space (black red line in inset in C; B and E). This result suggests that SR Ca 2006 ; [CITATION_3] . PKC ␣ and Ca V 1.2 voltagedependent Ca 2+ channels are each expressed in the smooth muscle cells being studied ( Fig. 8, A and B ) . To test the proposal that PKC ␣ may induce constitutive activity, the PKC activator indolactam-V (10 μ M) was applied to the cells and the voltage protocols ( Figs. 6 and 7 ) were repeated. In these experiments, depolarization ( Ϫ 70 to +10 mV) activated a voltage-dependent Ca 2+ current (I Ca ) and increased [Ca 2+ ] c ; the latter returned toward basal levels when the depolarization ended ( Fig. 8 C ) (I Ca in indolactam was signifi cantly [P < 0.05] greater than in its absence, as expected from the effects of PKC on voltage-dependent Ca 2+ channels [e.g., [CITATION_4] ). Next, the blocker nimodipine (1 μ M) was applied from the puffer pipette but again produced no signifi cant change in [Ca 2+ ] c . Thus, in control, resting bulk average [Ca 2+ ] was 1.1 ± 0.09 (F/F 0 ), whereas after 1 μ M nimodipine it was 1.1 ± 0.09 (F/F 0 ; n = 8; P > 0.05). Resting subplasma membrane [Ca 2+ ] in control was 1.16 ± 0.08 (F/F 0 ), and after 1 μ M nimodipine it was 1.18 ± 0.08 (F/F 0 ; n = 8; P > 0.05) ( Fig. 8 C ) . In contrast, I Ca light chain kinase and phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase) and could have prevented persistent Ca 2+ sparklets from developing. In a separate series of experiments (not depicted), as a control, wortmannin was omitted from the cells during Ca 2+ indicator loading and the hyperpolarization protocol was repeated. In these experiments, the hyperpolarization (to Ϫ 130 mV from Ϫ 70 mV) evoked a [Ca 2+ ] rise in the subplasma plasma membrane space (0.32 ± 0.19 ⌬ F/F 0 ; n = 4) and bulk cytoplasm (0.31 ± 0.19 ⌬ F/F 0 ; n = 4). 1 μ M nimodipine blocked neither the hyperpolarization-evoked [Ca 2+ ] c increase in the subplasma membrane space (0.84 ± 0.52 ⌬ F/F 0 ; n = 4) nor bulk cytoplasm (0.85 ± 0.5 ⌬ F/F 0 ; n = 4; P > 0.05)(not depicted). Again, this experiment suggests that those channels that control bulk average [Ca 2+ ] c were not constitutively active dihydropyridine-sensitive channels.",
